I recently had a new follower tell me this..
"I just gained so much respect for you" .. becaus so many profiles are filled with women who's bio says "Saved By Grace" .. then you scroll through their photo's and instantly feel like you need to put the phone down, scrub your eye's with soap and ask God to forgive you for seeing that .. What has happened to modesty these days!? ..I listened to a #PaulWasher Sermon a couple nights back and this is what I wrote down...⤵ "WHO DO I IMITATE?" & "DO I LOOK LIKE THE WORLD?" ..God has called us to be like who..? Every other girl from Hollywood we see on tv? 
The girl down the street? 
The girl on instagram? ..
The girl from that movie? ..NO! He has called us to be different!
To be like HIM! Let me tell ya, I would rather strive to be like Jesus then that girl on tv. The people on tv will change with the style, Jesus will NEVER CHANGE! 
Although.. it is hard when you see some pretty face with their hair done cute, makeup on point etc. and inside you feel this prick... a prick in your heart (from satan none the less) that says "hey, you should be like her, all the guys like her, and she is better than you,  you're nothing compared to her" .. but God says "No, be different, be like ME!" This life as a Christian is NOT about us, it's all about Jesus! And telling other's about Jesus and how to be saved!  We need to strive to BE LIKE JESUS! Not the people you see on tv... Ask God to mold you into what He wants! 
You won't regret it! 
And also... when you get dressed ask yourself "Will this cause someone (a man) to stumble, will it cause a woman to look down at her toes and feel that prick?  Maybe some women don't think like that.. but it's definitely an area I need to work on (comparison).. who's with me?  Instead of looking to others to compare ourselves,  let's strive to see how little we really are like Jesus and strive to be more like Him! 
#BeModest

I think the biggest problem with social media todag is that it mostly shows the highlights of people's life. We see the "peaks" while the "valley's" and struggle's remain hidden away. 
This wouldn't be a problem if it weren't for humanity's deep need to compare ourselves to others. The problem then is that we compare our own daily average to the highlight reel of others. 
We see the ripped and shredded model from a professional shoot or a show, but we don't see what he looks like 99% of the time. We don't see him packing on fat during the winter months to build muscle. We don't the see the 12 weeks this guy was on a strict diet to get ready, or that he didn't drink water for the last 24 hours leading up to the shoot to shed the remaining water weight.
We see a guy loving life on a yacht, but we don't see the 90 hour work week this guy has had for the last 20 years to be able to enjoy that yacht 2 hours a week.
We don't see the social and personal sacrifices these guys has made along the way.
We only see these highlights, and we don't understand what is wrong with us since our lives are basically a rollercoaster of mixed feelings, failures,setbacks,
 sprinkled with the odd victory.
On an unconscious level, we are led to believe that constant happiness and progress is the norm, since that is pretty much all we see!  This creates a deep feeling of discontent in people, which I believe is the root cause of much of the unhappiness people are experiencing today. 
Becoming consciously aware that what we see on social media is not the "full story" can be a good first step to remove that discontent✌🏽

Here is a little comparison of my hair length.
The picture above left shows my hair length in the middle 2011. I started growing them long again in 2010 when I had shoulder length hair (I didn't found a good photo of this).
The picture down left shows my hair length in the end of 2014. At that point I found the LHN (a longhair forum) and I found a length I wanted to reach. Before this I just thought of something like I had back in 2007 before I cutted them (It was around hip length). Now in May of 2017 (picture on the right) I reached that length goal I had: Classic length with 107cm according to SSS.
But already some month ago I thought about growing my hair longer than this. I started to dream about how I would look and feel with knee length hair. Now I am on my journey to find this out. 😄

One thing I have to mention in this moment.
My hair taught me a lot in this years, specially in the last one.
First of all to be patient. Growing hair long needs time. I know this and yeah I am still unpatient sometimes and don't want to wait for something. But I can see some things relexed, because I got to know that they are not able from now to the next moment.
Second to be happy about baby steps. I was frustrated a lot of times, because I wanted something and I felt like I never going to reach it, that I am not good enough. I didn't saw a progress or soemthing like this. Most times I just didn't saw that progress, but it was there. I just didn't noticed the small steps I was doing. Now I know that I have to look closer and that this baby steps are okay for me, this is the time I need for the progress. When I would force me to bigger steps it would just make me unhappy and feeling bad, so I guess I can be happy about every baby step I am doing. Hopefully constant like my hair is growing around 1cm in one month. It brings me further to my goal.
The third point is to never give up even it is hard. When I want to reach it I have to try it. When I fall down I have to stand up again. And when I have to do this thousend of times. When I real want to do soemthing than it worth it. Just like my hair never gives up in growing long even I cutted it. It tries it again and again.
